05316nam a22009495i 9780520915220DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209152207 a10.1525/97805209152202doi  a(DE-B1597)544141  a(OCoLC)1149432291  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD6060.6b.W55 1995eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a306.3/6152201 aWilliams, Christine L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStill a Man's World :bMen Who Do Women's Work /cChristine L. Williams.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (243 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMen and Masculinity ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Gendered Jobs and Gendered Workers -- t2. The Rise and Fall of the "Women's Professions" -- t3. An Unconventional Career Choice -- t4. Token Men in Training -- t5. Riding the Glass Escalator -- t6. Masculinity in "Feminine" Occupations -- t7. Occupational Segregation and Gender Inequality -- t8. Conclusion -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMen who do "women's work" have consistently been the butt of jokes, derided for their lack of drive and masculinity. In this eye-opening study, Christine Williams provides a wholly new look at men who work in predominantly female jobs. Having conducted extensive interviews in four cities, Williams uncovers how men in four occupations—nursing, elementary school teaching, librarianship, and social work—think about themselves and experience their work.Contrary to popular imagery, men in traditionally female occupations do not define themselves differently from men in more traditional occupations. Williams finds that most embrace conventional, masculine values. Her findings about how these men fare in their jobs are also counterintuitive. Rather than being surpassed by the larger number of women around them, these men experience the "glass escalator effect," rising in disproportionate numbers to administrative jobs at the top of their professions. Williams finds that a complex interplay between gendered expectations embedded in organizations, and the socially determined ideas workers bring to their jobs, contribute to mens' advantages in these occupations.Using a feminist psychoanalytic perspective, Williams calls for more men not only to cross over to women's occupations, but also to develop alternative masculinities that find common ground with traditionally female norms of cooperation and caring. Until the workplace is sexually integrated and masculine and feminine norms equally valued, it will unfortunately remain "still a man's world."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSex discrimination against men. 0aSex discrimination in employment. 0aSex role in the work environment. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aadministration.  aadministrative jobs.  aeconomic relations.  aelementary school education.  aelementary school teaching.  aemployment.  afeminism.  afeminist perspective.  agender studies.  agender.  agendered expectations.  agendered jobs.  aglass escalator effect.  aindustrial relations.  alabor.  alibrarians.  alibrarianship.  amasculine values.  amasculinity studies.  amasculinity.  amen and masculinity book series.  amen.  anurses.  anursing.  apredominantly female jobs.  asocial work.  awomens work.  awork.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000